WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.740 align:middle line:90%


00:00:07.740 --> 00:00:09.920 align:middle line:84%
So what's the
shape of our future?

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:12.470 align:middle line:10%
Are we racing for
ecological catastrophe

00:00:12.470 --> 00:00:15.880 align:middle line:10%
and total surveillance, or will
technology liberate humanity

00:00:15.880 --> 00:00:18.350 align:middle line:10%
from all constraints as
we learn to change our DNA

00:00:18.350 --> 00:00:19.720 align:middle line:10%
and merge with machines?

00:00:19.720 --> 00:00:22.180 align:middle line:84%
On this episode, we're
speaking with John Peterson

00:00:22.180 --> 00:00:24.050 align:middle line:84%
of the Arlington
Institute, a futurist

00:00:24.050 --> 00:00:25.910 align:middle line:84%
think tank, and
Carter Cleveland,

00:00:25.910 --> 00:00:28.880 align:middle line:84%
the CEO of artsy.net,
about what lies ahead.

00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:30.660 align:middle line:84%
We're going to look at how
social technologies can

00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:33.030 align:middle line:84%
transform the art
world, and how art

00:00:33.030 --> 00:00:36.130 align:middle line:84%
could provide the model for how
we redesign society as a whole.

00:00:36.130 --> 00:00:58.932 align:middle line:90%


00:00:58.932 --> 00:01:00.465 align:middle line:84%
DANIEL PINCHBECK: What's
exciting you the most

00:01:00.465 --> 00:01:01.570 align:middle line:90%
at Fashion Week this week?

00:01:01.570 --> 00:01:02.835 align:middle line:90%
The outfits are amazing.

00:01:02.835 --> 00:01:05.330 align:middle line:84%
We just saw J. Manuel
and June Ambrose.

00:01:05.330 --> 00:01:07.800 align:middle line:84%
I've been liking a
lot of the edgy looks.

00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:09.900 align:middle line:84%
A lot of spikes and
rhinestones and diamonds.

00:01:09.900 --> 00:01:12.580 align:middle line:84%
The Thakoon show is
extremely exciting.

00:01:12.580 --> 00:01:13.280 align:middle line:90%
Organza.

00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:14.680 align:middle line:90%
Organza's everywhere right now.

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:16.870 align:middle line:84%
Polka dots and some plaid,
like all mixed together.

00:01:16.870 --> 00:01:18.160 align:middle line:90%
Men with skirts.

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:20.800 align:middle line:84%
Leather boots or sandals that
go up to-- above the knee,

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:21.970 align:middle line:84%
wrapped in leather,
that probably

00:01:21.970 --> 00:01:23.337 align:middle line:90%
take 10 minutes to put on.

00:01:23.337 --> 00:01:24.870 align:middle line:84%
Did you make the clothes
that you're wearing?

00:01:24.870 --> 00:01:25.674 align:middle line:90%
No, not today.

00:01:25.674 --> 00:01:26.640 align:middle line:90%
I made the headpiece, though.

00:01:26.640 --> 00:01:29.540 align:middle line:90%
Sohan design coat jacket.

00:01:29.540 --> 00:01:31.511 align:middle line:84%
$2,800 purse?
Wow.

00:01:31.511 --> 00:01:32.210 align:middle line:90%
This one?

00:01:32.210 --> 00:01:33.890 align:middle line:84%
My gloves are by
Patricia Fields.

00:01:33.890 --> 00:01:35.110 align:middle line:84%
I consider myself
a walking canvas.

00:01:35.110 --> 00:01:36.680 align:middle line:84%
You guys have a
spiritual belief?

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:40.875 align:middle line:84%
I believe there's something
inside of us-- there's a kind

00:01:40.875 --> 00:01:43.450 align:middle line:90%
of a spirit or an energy.

00:01:43.450 --> 00:01:46.250 align:middle line:84%
I think that we're
all connected.

00:01:46.250 --> 00:01:49.110 align:middle line:84%
Well, we're from the
Bay Area, so we're really

00:01:49.110 --> 00:01:50.990 align:middle line:90%
in touch with our spirituality.

00:01:50.990 --> 00:01:53.020 align:middle line:84%
(LAUGHING) What do
you mean, spirituality?

00:01:53.020 --> 00:01:54.680 align:middle line:90%
I follow my ancestors' path.

00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:57.890 align:middle line:84%
I've grown up Catholic,
so I believe in heaven.

00:01:57.890 --> 00:02:00.210 align:middle line:84%
Do you think our
immortal soul continues

00:02:00.210 --> 00:02:02.544 align:middle line:84%
to dress itself up in
flamboyant, fashionable

00:02:02.544 --> 00:02:04.550 align:middle line:84%
outfits, even after death?
-Probably.

00:02:04.550 --> 00:02:07.298 align:middle line:90%
Yes, probably.

00:02:07.298 --> 00:02:09.900 align:middle line:84%
Hello, people of the world,
and welcome to Mind Shift.

00:02:09.900 --> 00:02:11.630 align:middle line:10%
I'm your host, Daniel Pinchbeck.

00:02:11.630 --> 00:02:14.280 align:middle line:10%
Today I'm talking with the
extraordinary futurist,

00:02:14.280 --> 00:02:17.210 align:middle line:10%
founder of the Arlington
Institute, John Peterson.

00:02:17.210 --> 00:02:19.700 align:middle line:84%
And we'll be looking at future
trends, what's happening

00:02:19.700 --> 00:02:24.924 align:middle line:84%
in the cosmological,
technological, genetic future,

00:02:24.924 --> 00:02:26.090 align:middle line:84%
what do we have to
look forward to.

00:02:26.090 --> 00:02:27.380 align:middle line:84%
And I'm sure it'll
be an awesome,

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:28.880 align:middle line:90%
fascinating discussion.

00:02:28.880 --> 00:02:31.600 align:middle line:84%
NARRATOR: A naval flight
officers in the US Navy, John

00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:34.350 align:middle line:84%
L. Peterson has worked at
various military institutions

00:02:34.350 --> 00:02:35.740 align:middle line:90%
in the United States.

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:38.440 align:middle line:84%
In 1989 he founded the
Arlington Institute,

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:40.170 align:middle line:84%
a futurist think
tank specializing

00:02:40.170 --> 00:02:42.530 align:middle line:84%
in predictive modeling
of future events.

00:02:42.530 --> 00:02:44.380 align:middle line:84%
The main objective of
the Arlington Institute

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:46.930 align:middle line:84%
is to discover the early
indicators of transition,

00:02:46.930 --> 00:02:48.580 align:middle line:90%
and to provide solutions.

00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:51.990 align:middle line:84%
He was awarded Outstanding
Academic Book in 1995

00:02:51.990 --> 00:02:55.580 align:middle line:84%
by Choice Academic Review for
his work, The Road to 2015:

00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:58.400 align:middle line:84%
Profiles of the Future, and is
acclaimed as one of the world's

00:02:58.400 --> 00:02:59.677 align:middle line:90%
most important futurists.

00:02:59.677 --> 00:03:02.539 align:middle line:90%


00:03:02.539 --> 00:03:05.401 align:middle line:84%
[APPLAUSE]
-Daniel.

00:03:05.401 --> 00:03:06.360 align:middle line:90%
John, it's nice to see you.

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:08.189 align:middle line:84%
Thanks so much for coming today.
-Thanks.

00:03:08.189 --> 00:03:10.180 align:middle line:84%
So tell me a little bit
about-- how did you get

00:03:10.180 --> 00:03:11.600 align:middle line:90%
so interested in the future?

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:14.550 align:middle line:84%
Hmm, oh, that's a long,
kind of circuitous story.

00:03:14.550 --> 00:03:17.730 align:middle line:10%
But I was working
in the White House,

00:03:17.730 --> 00:03:21.850 align:middle line:10%
and looking out at
the kind of the future

00:03:21.850 --> 00:03:25.210 align:middle line:10%
of the military and
national security,

00:03:25.210 --> 00:03:28.390 align:middle line:10%
and ended up going
out and looking

00:03:28.390 --> 00:03:32.270 align:middle line:10%
at breakthrough technologies
and strange science,

00:03:32.270 --> 00:03:33.290 align:middle line:10%
and other kinds of things.

00:03:33.290 --> 00:03:35.310 align:middle line:84%
And what I figured
out was that there

00:03:35.310 --> 00:03:38.800 align:middle line:84%
was this convergence--
this was back 20 years

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:39.805 align:middle line:90%
ago-- there's a convergence.

00:03:39.805 --> 00:03:42.860 align:middle line:84%
There are these big things
that were all coming together,

00:03:42.860 --> 00:03:46.650 align:middle line:84%
climate change and technology
and social value shifts.

00:03:46.650 --> 00:03:48.970 align:middle line:84%
They were all coming
together inexorably,

00:03:48.970 --> 00:03:51.660 align:middle line:84%
and going to fundamentally
change who we all were.

00:03:51.660 --> 00:03:53.970 align:middle line:84%
And then one day somebody
said, oh you're a futurist,

00:03:53.970 --> 00:03:55.610 align:middle line:90%
said I said, oh, OK.

00:03:55.610 --> 00:04:00.000 align:middle line:84%
But I've been fascinated
about it all ever since.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.280 align:middle line:84%
So how is the future looking
from where we are now?

00:04:02.280 --> 00:04:04.490 align:middle line:90%
It's extraordinary, Daniel.

00:04:04.490 --> 00:04:07.190 align:middle line:84%
We're at this amazing
kind of transition

00:04:07.190 --> 00:04:09.740 align:middle line:90%
in time that's unprecedented.

00:04:09.740 --> 00:04:12.230 align:middle line:84%
That essentially,
in my opinion, we're

00:04:12.230 --> 00:04:16.720 align:middle line:84%
at a period-- we're at the
punctuation in the evolution

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:17.720 align:middle line:90%
of the species.

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:20.124 align:middle line:84%
You can go back, way back,
to single cellular life,

00:04:20.124 --> 00:04:23.671 align:middle line:84%
and multiple cellular life,
and vertebrates and mammals

00:04:23.671 --> 00:04:24.370 align:middle line:90%
and so on.

00:04:24.370 --> 00:04:28.570 align:middle line:84%
And there's a regular
predictable period,

00:04:28.570 --> 00:04:31.290 align:middle line:84%
cyclical period,
that each time you

00:04:31.290 --> 00:04:33.750 align:middle line:84%
can predict that there's
going to be these major kind

00:04:33.750 --> 00:04:34.670 align:middle line:90%
of transitions.

00:04:34.670 --> 00:04:36.880 align:middle line:84%
And we're at one
of those right now.

00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:38.670 align:middle line:84%
And what's going
to come out of it?

00:04:38.670 --> 00:04:40.120 align:middle line:84%
And it's going to
be quite obvious.

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:43.080 align:middle line:84%
It's already mainline; science
is coming to the conclusion

00:04:43.080 --> 00:04:46.120 align:middle line:84%
that grandchildren and
great grandchildren

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:48.700 align:middle line:84%
are going to be genetically
different than who

00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:49.670 align:middle line:90%
we are right now.

00:04:49.670 --> 00:04:52.070 align:middle line:84%
So there's a new human
that's emerging out of this.

00:04:52.070 --> 00:04:56.370 align:middle line:84%
And it's enabled by a number of
things, including cosmic energy

00:04:56.370 --> 00:04:57.770 align:middle line:90%
and technology and so on.

00:04:57.770 --> 00:04:59.130 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, I'm a little confused.

00:04:59.130 --> 00:05:01.200 align:middle line:84%
Let's just take a pause
on that for a second.

00:05:01.200 --> 00:05:02.930 align:middle line:84%
I'm a little confused
about what you're saying

00:05:02.930 --> 00:05:05.670 align:middle line:90%
about this genetic change.

00:05:05.670 --> 00:05:07.110 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you're not
saying it's going

00:05:07.110 --> 00:05:10.220 align:middle line:84%
to be caused by genetic
engineering, or biotechnology,

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:15.970 align:middle line:84%
or by us merging with machines
in a Kurzweillian sense, or a--

00:05:15.970 --> 00:05:17.720 align:middle line:84%
Ray Kurzweil is
a friend, but I'm

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:20.750 align:middle line:90%
not a fan of that whole notion.

00:05:20.750 --> 00:05:23.710 align:middle line:84%
Which is not to say that
technology and science is not

00:05:23.710 --> 00:05:25.640 align:middle line:90%
going to have its role to play.

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:27.810 align:middle line:84%
The notion we're talking
about is the singularity idea

00:05:27.810 --> 00:05:30.560 align:middle line:84%
that Ray Kurzweil has
populated, that somehow

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:33.160 align:middle line:84%
humans and technology, man and
machine, are going to merge.

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:35.790 align:middle line:84%
And we'll have, like, nanobots
in all of our organs--

00:05:35.790 --> 00:05:37.030 align:middle line:84%
Right, running
around in your brain.

00:05:37.030 --> 00:05:39.210 align:middle line:84%
Do the breathing
for us, and so on.

00:05:39.210 --> 00:05:42.950 align:middle line:84%
And I don't doubt that that's
all possible at some point,

00:05:42.950 --> 00:05:43.920 align:middle line:90%
and that it plays a role.

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:47.830 align:middle line:84%
I mean, right now, there're only
probably half a dozen organs

00:05:47.830 --> 00:05:50.130 align:middle line:84%
in your body that
cannot be artificially

00:05:50.130 --> 00:05:51.790 align:middle line:90%
produced in one way or another.

00:05:51.790 --> 00:05:54.960 align:middle line:84%
And they're manufacturing
these things with 3D printers.

00:05:54.960 --> 00:05:56.810 align:middle line:84%
And so, I mean, sure.
Technology--

00:05:56.810 --> 00:05:59.650 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, I want to note
that John's-- the Arlington

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:02.050 align:middle line:84%
Institute publishes
The Future Edition,

00:06:02.050 --> 00:06:04.500 align:middle line:84%
which is-- I totally recommend
people subscribing to it.

00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:09.270 align:middle line:84%
It's a wonderful
compendium of news stories,

00:06:09.270 --> 00:06:12.500 align:middle line:84%
essays, kind of really
gives you a sense

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:15.760 align:middle line:84%
of the divergent potential
that we're moving into.

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:16.530 align:middle line:90%
And it's free.

00:06:16.530 --> 00:06:18.740 align:middle line:90%
And it's free.

00:06:18.740 --> 00:06:20.901 align:middle line:84%
So what do you mean by
genetic transformation

00:06:20.901 --> 00:06:21.600 align:middle line:90%
of the human species?

00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:23.090 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's really
quite interesting.

00:06:23.090 --> 00:06:26.860 align:middle line:84%
Because certainly there's
any number of things

00:06:26.860 --> 00:06:29.220 align:middle line:84%
that we're doing to our
cells, and that science

00:06:29.220 --> 00:06:32.030 align:middle line:84%
is doing, that probably
that's going to influence.

00:06:32.030 --> 00:06:37.020 align:middle line:84%
And there's genetic engineering
going on, forever, in every way

00:06:37.020 --> 00:06:39.180 align:middle line:90%
that you can think about it.

00:06:39.180 --> 00:06:41.800 align:middle line:84%
But the most fascinating
thing, and the thing

00:06:41.800 --> 00:06:46.220 align:middle line:84%
that's compatible with
this generational shift,

00:06:46.220 --> 00:06:50.210 align:middle line:84%
is that there are now
numerous sources that suggest

00:06:50.210 --> 00:06:53.450 align:middle line:84%
that there's different kind
energy coming out of the sun

00:06:53.450 --> 00:06:54.990 align:middle line:84%
and out of the
center of the galaxy

00:06:54.990 --> 00:06:56.430 align:middle line:90%
that we haven't seen before.

00:06:56.430 --> 00:07:00.371 align:middle line:84%
And it's coming over a
period of time, over decades.

00:07:00.371 --> 00:07:01.070 align:middle line:90%
But--

00:07:01.070 --> 00:07:03.130 align:middle line:84%
What's the evidence
that backs that up?

00:07:03.130 --> 00:07:07.490 align:middle line:84%
Well, there's NASA measurements
and other kind of things that

00:07:07.490 --> 00:07:09.200 align:middle line:84%
certainly show
that the energy is

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:11.090 align:middle line:84%
changing, that there
are certain aspects

00:07:11.090 --> 00:07:12.350 align:middle line:90%
of the energy that's changing.

00:07:12.350 --> 00:07:14.930 align:middle line:84%
I mean, weren't we expecting
a solar maximum, that

00:07:14.930 --> 00:07:16.190 align:middle line:90%
kind of hasn't really happened?

00:07:16.190 --> 00:07:17.880 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah.

00:07:17.880 --> 00:07:19.370 align:middle line:84%
The last week, as
a matter of fact,

00:07:19.370 --> 00:07:21.040 align:middle line:84%
there just were--
for a number of days,

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:25.020 align:middle line:84%
there were almost
no solar spots.

00:07:25.020 --> 00:07:27.470 align:middle line:84%
And I remember reading
that the heliosphere, which

00:07:27.470 --> 00:07:29.150 align:middle line:84%
is kind of a protective
energy the sun puts out,

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:30.750 align:middle line:84%
has actually
decreased in strength,

00:07:30.750 --> 00:07:32.300 align:middle line:90%
like 50% over the last decades.

00:07:32.300 --> 00:07:33.150 align:middle line:90%
It has.

00:07:33.150 --> 00:07:36.270 align:middle line:84%
And so there's a combination
of these kinds of things.

00:07:36.270 --> 00:07:37.780 align:middle line:84%
And what's happening,
also, to the earth's

00:07:37.780 --> 00:07:39.160 align:middle line:90%
electromagnetic field?

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:42.350 align:middle line:84%
Well, the magnetic
field is also decreasing,

00:07:42.350 --> 00:07:44.080 align:middle line:84%
and that's part of
the problem as well.

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:48.660 align:middle line:84%
Because what that does is effect
the amount of the cosmic rays

00:07:48.660 --> 00:07:50.300 align:middle line:84%
that can come from
not only the sun,

00:07:50.300 --> 00:07:52.180 align:middle line:84%
but also from the
center the galaxy.

00:07:52.180 --> 00:07:55.650 align:middle line:84%
Do we have any idea as to
why the electromagnetic field

00:07:55.650 --> 00:07:56.560 align:middle line:90%
of the earth is decreasing?

00:07:56.560 --> 00:07:57.270 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, sure.

00:07:57.270 --> 00:08:00.400 align:middle line:90%
Because a couple of reasons.

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:03.030 align:middle line:84%
There's a regular
kind of magnetic pole

00:08:03.030 --> 00:08:04.800 align:middle line:90%
shift that goes on.

00:08:04.800 --> 00:08:09.080 align:middle line:84%
And what we've been seeing
for the last 150 years

00:08:09.080 --> 00:08:15.622 align:middle line:84%
is a decrease in the
amount of the intensity

00:08:15.622 --> 00:08:19.560 align:middle line:84%
in the definition of the
north and south magnetic pole.

00:08:19.560 --> 00:08:25.926 align:middle line:84%
And now it's starting to morph,
and it's a rapidly changing.

00:08:25.926 --> 00:08:29.380 align:middle line:84%
And what they believe is
that in the next, maybe 20

00:08:29.380 --> 00:08:30.870 align:middle line:84%
years or something
like that, you

00:08:30.870 --> 00:08:33.260 align:middle line:90%
might get a literal pole shift.

00:08:33.260 --> 00:08:34.960 align:middle line:84%
When you say they, who
are some of the most

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:36.770 align:middle line:84%
credible scientists or
researchers that people might--

00:08:36.770 --> 00:08:37.220 align:middle line:90%
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:08:37.220 --> 00:08:38.453 align:middle line:84%
Oh, I couldn't tell
you individuals,

00:08:38.453 --> 00:08:39.700 align:middle line:90%
but this is broadly based.

00:08:39.700 --> 00:08:44.490 align:middle line:84%
And it's in NASA
and NOAA and it's

00:08:44.490 --> 00:08:47.920 align:middle line:84%
just not a question at all
about magnetic pole shift.

00:08:47.920 --> 00:08:50.100 align:middle line:84%
Well then, do you share,
kind of, the hypothesis

00:08:50.100 --> 00:08:52.010 align:middle line:84%
of certain thinkers
like Jose Arguelles,

00:08:52.010 --> 00:08:54.700 align:middle line:84%
for instance, or more mystical
thinkers like [INAUDIBLE],

00:08:54.700 --> 00:09:00.110 align:middle line:84%
maybe, that somehow humanity
is in an evolutionary process

00:09:00.110 --> 00:09:01.670 align:middle line:84%
that involves this
transformation

00:09:01.670 --> 00:09:02.470 align:middle line:90%
of consciousness?

00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:05.861 align:middle line:84%
That somehow synchronized to
these larger cosmic processes?

00:09:05.861 --> 00:09:06.870 align:middle line:84%
Absolutely.
Absolutely.

00:09:06.870 --> 00:09:09.870 align:middle line:84%
And that's the-- and this
is the-- first of all,

00:09:09.870 --> 00:09:11.000 align:middle line:90%
it's not magic.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:12.990 align:middle line:84%
It's only magic if you
can't understand it.

00:09:12.990 --> 00:09:15.990 align:middle line:84%
So something is going on that's
understandable, if you're

00:09:15.990 --> 00:09:17.210 align:middle line:90%
able to understand it.

00:09:17.210 --> 00:09:20.790 align:middle line:84%
And what I'm suggesting is that
in the context of those kinds

